Merge pull request #1562 from chadian/ember-intl-implementation-fixes

ember-intl implementation fixes
Fix navigation locale translation fallback

Fix right-to-left support lost from ember-i18n to ember-intl migration

- Change the css implmentation to use the root body direction attribute.
- Use rtl-detect instead of managing rtl configuration
Change existing rtl (right-to-left language) css to use body dir attribute selector
Fix the way language preference is set and saved with fallback locale
Add language-select test to check changes in locale reflect default option

Swap pbkdf2 usage to use npm package directly

Previously with ember-browserify, browserify would use the crypto package
crypto-browserify, which wrapped individual browser-safe crypto packages.
By dropping ember-browserify we can use the pbkdf2 package directly along
with ember-auto-import.

Remove npm-prefixed package imports

ember-browserify required that package imports be prefixed with "npm:",
but with ember-auto-import they can be imported directly by their package
name.

Add pouchdb to ember-auto-import excludes

This ensures that the PouchDB module used is the one shimmed by
ember-pouch which includes additional required pouchdb plugins.

Rename deprecated jquery helpers to their own files

Some tests require on the jquery query engine to select elements
based on selectors that aren't compatible with document.querySelector
which the new ember test helpers use. To maintain this for now we
introduce a deprecated selector to warn against using these in the future,
but allow tests that currently need them to still pass.

Introduce ember-concurrency with examples (#977)

* Add ember-concurrency addon version 0.7.19

* Refactor admin/address/route to use e-c

This is the example I used in issue #969. It is illustrates how to use
ember-concurrency tasks in routes.

* Refactor patients/delete/controller to use e-c

Example of using ember-concurrency tasks to manage a complex promise
chain of events. I picked this one mainly because I wanted to illustrate
the simplicity of using e-c tasks to manage what was otherwise a very
complex promise chain.

I tried to preserve some of the concurrency described in the previous
promise based code. However, after some analysis and discussion on the
Ember Slack channels difference between preserving the concurrency and
just running the resolutions serially are likely very small. In this
case the use of `all()` could likely be removed without a significant
impact on performance. I mention this later optimisation as a way to
make the code even easier to grok. I'll leave the debate to further
discussion.
